Tell HN: WFH is the future thanks to inconsiderate people
text:
I'm very recent to the workforce (less than 6 months into my first job ever).

Today a co-worker came in with a constant, never ending cough. According to her "it's from singing too many Christmas Carols" this last weekend, but I doubt that.

She's obviously not wearing a mask, not even one of those cloth ones. Heck, she doesn't even cover her mouth when she coughs.

Not only it is annoying, but it's a reasonable health hazard I thought everyone post-2020 understood could be easily avoided if you stayed home.

Nobody cares, I'm the only one who's fully masked up.

I cannot fully WFH as I'm not in tech, but as an office worker, it's the future with these kinds of people.

Rust Developer
text:
seeks a talented engineer, fluent in Rust, Ruby, and/or Python, for a full-time, remote opportunity. Our ideal candidate is a Senior (5+ years) backend engineer, with experience building scalable production applications, working with large data sets, and owning the entire development lifecycle. We are building and maintaining software using Rust to ingest, parse, process, and serve significant datasets, making use of SIMD, Apache Arrow, Apache DataFusion, Polars, and similar technologies. Our team manages a product of our own that helps drive an essential segment of our business.

You might be a good fit if you have: • Bachelor’s degree or equivalent experience • 5+ years in a Software Engineer role • Experience developing systems in AWS • Experience building software to support large, complex datasets • Extensive experience with relational databases and data model design • Experience with AWS, Docker, SQL, Unix, and DevOps. • Embraces a DevOps mindset and software engineering best practices (source control, testing, code review) • Experience with Apache Arrow/DataFusion/Polars a plus

How does iOS know which apps can receive “calls”?
text:
This morning, out of the blue, someone I know called me -- on Facebook Messenger, on my iPhone. I was happy to hear from him, but also puzzled: I have all notifications for Facebook and Messenger turned off, and I wasn't even AWARE that a "call" function existed for Messenger.

I also have a softphone tool on my phone (Nextiva) plus Teams, for work. I can receive "calls" via either of those tools, too. In those cases, that behavior is welcome; not so for Facebook. It wasn't until today that I realized "gee, I never told my phone to let those things do "call" behavior".

Is there really not somewhere in the iOS settings where I can control whether or not an app has access to telephony-style behavior? Or have I just missed it?

Ask HN: Reading on esoteric side of “tick-tock” silicon business strategy?
text:
Question: Can HN please recommend specific things to read to understand any potentially lesser-known but interesting history of the "tick tock" strategy famously used for silicon chip improvements and rollouts for the past decades?

Background: the popularly known version is something along the lines of: like clockwork, CPU improvement cycles consist of "tick" (shrink the architecture a little), then "tock" (improve the architecture), then repeated.

This obviously resulted in a long term trend of upgrades and capability increases.

I want to know: is there documented history from the silicon industry of esoteric or lesser known business and engineering stories about "tick tock". For example, could it have been possible or at least discussed to "move ahead" more rapidly, but instead, it made (far) more business and political sense to inch things along?

Note: - I anticipate a popular refrain saying that you have to innovate little by little, by the very nature of the improvements. - I also anticipate that even a "broad and deep" traditional understanding/education of computer engineering and its history might not uncover this particular topic. - Searching the web, it is sort of hard to find coverage of this exact topic I am looking for, even just to understand it better broadly.

Does HN understand the question, and, if so, has this topic been covered somewhere? Any books, oral histories, articles (academic or general), websites, or even documentary videos on the subject would be appreciated.

Thanks in advance!

Aside/clarification: This question is only really about the hardware/chip/CPU aspects. There are related issues in software, systems, augmentation, etc. that I understand somewhat more about regarding issues of "missed/impossible leaps" and computer-human evolution/uptake, but this question is not about those issues really.
